<DOC><DOCNO> AP891206-0027 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-12-06-89 0322EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r w PM-WashingtonInBrief     12-06 0415</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Washington In Brief,420</SECOND><HEAD>Health Officials: Climate Changes Threaten to Spread Disease</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   While changes in the Earth's climate threatento encourage the spread of diseases like rabies, the changes mayalso damage the human body's ability to fight them, healthofficials are warning.   A conference on ``Global Atmospheric Change and Public Health''was told Tuesday that potential problems stem both from theincrease in ultraviolet radiation, as the protective ozone layer inthe stratosphere is damaged, and from climate warming, which manyscientists believe is occurring in a so-called Greenhouse effect.   Ultraviolet radiation, already known to cause skin cancer, alsohas a major effect in reducing the response of the human immunesystem, said Dr. Raymond Daynes of the University of Utah.   At the same time the immune system damage is being threatened,warming of the climate could lead to the spread of diseasescurrently limited by the climate, said Dr. Robert E. Shope of theYale University School of Medicine.</TEXT><HEAD>Measure Signed by Bush Protects Nevada Wilderness</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   More land in Nevada would be protected fromdevelopment, timber harvesting and mineral exploration underlegislation that has been signed into law by President Bush.   The measure, signed Tuesday, creates 733,400 acres of protectedwilderness in Nevada and opens another 2.4 million acres tomultiple use under the management of the Agriculture Department.   The legislation puts a total of 2 percent of the state's landunder wilderness protection, preventing development and such usesas timber harvesting, mineral exploration or intrusion by campersin vehicles.   However, the legislation protects existing grazing rights forranchers on the wilderness land, and low-level military flightsover four of the new wilderness areas, a White House spokesman said.</TEXT><HEAD>Safety Panel: School Bleachers at Risk of Collapsing</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Certain indoor school bleachers are at risk ofcollapsing because of poor maintenance and improper operation,school officials are being told.   The Consumer Product Safety Commission warned schooladministrators nationwide Tuesday that bleachers should beroutinely inspected and maintained at least twice a year.   In addition, only trained personnel, not students, should beused to operate the bleachers, the commission said in a statement.   The commission said recent collapses of school gymnasiumbleachers prompted the warning, which involves manual, telescopingbleachers made from 1966 to 1979 by Michigan-based Interkal andsold under the trade names ``Brunswick,'' ``Vecta'' and``Interkal.''   The commission said 16 collapses since 1978 have produced back,arm, leg and ankle injuries.</TEXT></DOC>